vectorData.altText: 10. Lesion of a cranial nerve always has ipsilateral effects.
That's right!  Lesions of a cranial nerve always have ipsilateral effects. This is also true of cranial nerve nuclei, that their lesion has ipsilateral effects, with one exception. What is it?
That is incorrect. Click here      to learn the answer, then come back to try again.

In the spinal cord:
remember: LMNs of the ventral horn innervate ipsilateral targets
 LMN lesions in the spinal cord, of a spinal nerve, or of a peripheral nerve ALWAYS have ipsilateral effects
In the brainstem:
LMNs in cranial nerve nuclei also innervate ipsilateral targets
 lesions of a CN nucleus containing LMNs OR of a cranial nerve containing motor axons ALWAYS have ipsilateral effects
with ONE (unimportant) EXCEPTION.

LMNs in the trochlear nucleus decussate, therefore:
contralateral deficits with lesion of the trochlear nucleus 
BUT: 
ipsilateral deficits with lesion of the trochlear nerve
